            <h2>Introduction & Abstract</h2>
            
            <p>This website presents a comprehensive and in-depth analysis of the Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP), the foundational application-layer protocol of the World Wide Web. We trace HTTP's evolution through its major versions, examining the architectural and performance challenges that drove its developmentâ€”from the rudimentary origins of HTTP/0.9 to the modern, UDP-based QUIC protocol in HTTP/3.</p>
            
            <p>The core of HTTP's function is the regulated transaction of information, operating on the fundamental client-server concept. A client (browser) sends a request, and a server returns a response. Although its central role is to accelerate browser-server communication, HTTP's simple yet powerful design allows it to be used for many other purposes, such as accessing APIs and facilitating machine-to-machine communication.</p>
            
            <div class="content-card">
                <h3>Key Terms</h3>
                <!-- Code Comment: Using an unordered list for presenting key terms. -->
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>HTTP/0.9:</strong> The initial, simple version supporting only the GET method.</li>
                    <li><strong>HTTP/1.1:</strong> Introduced persistent connections to reduce TCP overhead.</li>
                    <li><strong>HTTP/2:</strong> Introduced multiplexing to solve Head-of-Line (HOL) blocking.</li>
                    <li><strong>HTTP/3:</strong> Uses the QUIC protocol over UDP for faster, more resilient connections.</li>
                    <li><strong>QUIC:</strong> A transport layer protocol designed to reduce latency compared to TCP.</li>
                    <li><strong>Multiplexing:</strong> The process of sending multiple requests and responses concurrently over a single connection.</li>
                    <li><strong>Client-Server Model:</strong> The fundamental interaction paradigm where the client initiates the request.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

